To begin with, we want to know what makes thoughts unlike other mental states. The answer is that thoughts are mental states that we have that have propositional content: that represent the world as being a certain way. When you think "it's nice out this morning," you're representing the world as being in a certain state, namely the one in which the weather is enjoyable. Other types of mental states are not propositional in this way, however, because they don't represent the world as being a certain way. For example, emotions feel a certain way, but they don't represent the world as being a certain way. One way to think about this is in terms of truth and falsity: while thoughts can be true or false, emotions can't. It doesn't make sense to say that your anger is true or false in the same way it does to say that your thoughts are true or false, because anger doesn't have propositional content: it doesn't represent the world as being a particular way.\
So, thoughts are mental states with propositional content, which represent the world as being a particular way. But how do we have them? The answer has to do with meaning: thoughts have propositional content because they mean something. The words (or, for some, images) that make up your thoughts have meanings, and these meanings combine to make up the propositional content of the thought. In your thought "it's nice out this morning", each individual word contributes its meaning to the proposition that is the content of the thought, which is that it's nice out this morning. So the trick to figuring out how there are thoughts in our brain is to figure out how states of our brain can be meaningful.\
The current theory about how our brain states can be meaningful stipulates that there's a language of thought: that just like our speech is composed of linguistic elements like words that have meaning, so too do our neurons combine in our brain to form language-like patterns of activation that are meaningful in the same way that language is. So certain local patterns of neural activation actually mean the same thing as the English words "morning", "nice," and so on, and different relations between those local patterns of neural activity serve the same logical function as English grammar, which allows individually meaningful words to combine to form a meaningful proposition that represents a particular state of the world. As a result, you have the English thought "it's nice out this morning" because your brain is thinking in its own, totally different language, which happens to mean the same thing as "it's nice out this morning."\
