\cf4 Now, how do those thoughts become conscious? This is an area of active research, but most philosophers and cognitive scientists are coalescing around what's called the 'global workspace model' of consciousness. On this view, thoughts are conscious when they're in a special kind of relationship with other states of the brain that allow them to cause and be caused by all kinds of other brain states. Most of our brain activity has only local causal relations: for example, the brain states that control our balance can only be caused by certain sensory neurons, and can only cause a limited range of motor responses. As a result, they're almost always unconscious. But thoughts become conscious when they can can cause and be caused by almost anything: by sensations, emotions, desires, other thoughts, and so on. In particular, one thing conscious thoughts can cause are conscious auditory imaginations - namely those of the English language words that we use to express the thought. Why conscious thoughts tend to do this is unclear, but it probably has to do with facilitating quick translation of thought to speech. Since your thoughts are in the neuronal language of thought, but you need to communicate in natural languages like English, it's helpful for the brain to have a way of quickly translating your conscious thoughts and relaying them to the parts of your brain that control speech.\
